window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>1","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"FUNDAMENTAL AND DERIVED QUANTITIES AND UNITS : FUNDAMENTAL QUANTITIES AND UNITS","question":"The diagram above illustrates a micrometer screw gauge. Determine its reading","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"2.44mm","B":"2.46mm","C":"2.86mm","D":"2.96mm"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The diagram in the question is that of a micrometer screw gauge.  Recall: To take the readings of a micrometer screw gauge, we take the sum of the main scale reading and the micro scale reading.  Micrometer Reading = Mainscale reading + Microscale reading  MR = MSR + msr ----------- (1)  MR = 2.00m + 0.46mm  = 2.46mm","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>2","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"DERIVED QUANTITIES AND DIMENSIONAL ANALYSIS :","question":"Which of the following dimensions represents impulse?","images":[],"options":{"A":"MLT-2","B":"MLT-1","C":"MLT","D":"ML"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Impulse = Ft  Force = ma  a = v/t ; v = d/l = l/t  a = LT-2  so force = MLT-2  Therefore, Impulse = Ft  = MLT-2 \u00d7 T = MLT-1","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>3","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"RECTILINEAR ACCELERATION : EQUATIONS OF MOTION WITH CONSTANT ACCELERATION","question":"A body accelerates uniformly from rest at 2ms-2. Calculate its velocity when it has travelled a distance of 9m.","images":[],"options":{"A":"3.0 ms-1","B":"4.5ms-1","C":"6.0ms-1","D":"18.0ms-1"},"answer":"C","explanation":"a = 2m/s2  u = 0  s = 9m   v = ?  using v2 = u2 + 2as  v2 = 02 + 2 x 2 x 9  v2 = 36  v =  &radic;36&nbsp; = 6m/s","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>4","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPTS OF MATTER : CONCEPTS OF MATTER","question":"Which of the following statements about matter is not correct?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Molecules of solids move more freely than molecules of liquids and gases","B":"Molecules of solids are more closely packed than those of the liquids","C":"Energy is required to break the intermolecular forces of attraction between molecules","D":"Molecules of liquids move about within the liquid and they are in constant random motion"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The molecules of gases move with the highest speed, followed by the molecules of liquid and then solids.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>5","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"MOTION : SIMPLE IDEAS OF CIRCULAR MOTION","question":"A ball is projected horizontally from the top of a tower. Neglecting air resistance, which of the following statements about its motion is/are correct?  I. Vertical acceleration on the ball decreases as it falls   II. The vertical force on the ball remains constant  III. The vertical speed of the ball increases as it falls","images":[],"options":{"A":"I only","B":"II only","C":"I and II only","D":"II and III only"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The vertical acceleration on the ball does not decrease as it falls, it remains constant due to gravity. Therefore, statement I is incorrect. The vertical force on the ball also remains constant, as it is the gravitational force acting on the ball. Therefore, statement II is correct. The vertical speed of the ball increases as it falls due to the constant acceleration from gravity. Therefore, statement III is correct. Hence, the correct option is 'II and III only'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>6","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"NEWTON\u2019S LAWS OF MOTION : SECOND LAW","question":"Two forces 100N and 60N act on an object of mass 10Kg as illustrated in the diagram above. Neglecting friction, calculate the acceleration of the object.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"4.0ms-2","B":"13.1ms-2","C":"16.0ms-1","D":"22.6ms-2"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Resolving 100N into horizontal and vertical  100sin45 = 70.71; 100cos45 = 70.71  vertical forces =100 -70.71 =29.29  Horizontal force = 70.71 + 60 = 130.71    Resultant of vertical and horizontal forces using pythagoras theorem  R = 133.9N from F = m2  a=Fm=133.910=13.4 m/s2","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>7","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"FLUID AT REST : EQUILIBRIUM OF BODIES: ARCHIMEDES\u2019 PRINCIPLE","question":"A body weighing 14N in air is partially immersed in water. If the mass of water displaced in the process is 200g, calculate the upthrust on the body. [g = 10ms-2]","images":[],"options":{"A":"2.0N","B":"3.0N","C":"3.5N","D":"7.0N"},"answer":"A","explanation":"W = 14N  mass of water displaced = 200g = 0.2kg  Upthrust = weight of the fluid displaced   = mass of the fluid displaced \u00d7 gravity  = 0.2kg \u00d7 10m/s2   = 2N","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>8","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : EVAPORATION AND BOILING","question":"Which of the following processes is not a surface phenomenon?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Condensation","B":"Evaporation","C":"Photoemission","D":"Thermionic emission"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The process that is not considered a surface phenomenon among the given options is:    Condensation.    While condensation involves the transition from a gas to a liquid at surfaces (like dew forming on grass), it occurs throughout the volume of the gas and liquid, making it more of a bulk phenomenon. The other processes listed (evaporation, photoemission, and thermionic emission) are closely related to the interactions occurring at surfaces.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>9","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"FUNDAMENTAL AND DERIVED QUANTITIES AND UNITS : FUNDAMENTAL QUANTITIES AND UNITS","question":"A chemical balance is used for measuring","images":[],"options":{"A":"volume","B":"mass","C":"thickness","D":"density"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A chemical balance is used for measuring mass. It is a device used in chemical laboratories for the precise measurement of small quantities of matter. It is not used for measuring volume, thickness or density.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>10","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"MOTION : SIMPLE IDEAS OF CIRCULAR MOTION","question":"A body is whirled round a circular path at constant speed. Which of the following diagrams correctly indicates the direction of the body's velocity (v) and acceleration (a)?","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"","B":"","C":"","D":""},"answer":"B","explanation":"For a body undergoing circular motion, the acceleration is directed towards the centre, and the velocity is directed round the circumference of the circle as we have in","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>11","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"MOTION : CONCEPT OF SPEED","question":"A motorist travelling at 72kmh-1 had his eyes shut for 0.4s during a hard sneeze. Calculate the distance covered by him during this time interval","images":[],"options":{"A":"50.0m","B":"28.8m","C":"18.0m","D":"8.0m"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Velocity=72kmh=72*times100360=20ms-1  Time = 0.4s, Distance, S = ?  FromS=ut+12at2  Since the motorist is travelling at 72km/h, it suggests that the velocity is constant, therefore, acceleration = 0  therefore, S = ut = 20 \u00d7 0.4 = 8m","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>12","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"PROJECTILE MOTION :","question":"The angle at which a projectile must be fired to cover maximum range is","images":[],"options":{"A":"30\u00b0","B":"45\u00b0","C":"60\u00b0","D":"90\u00b0"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The angle, \u03b8 at which aa projectile must be fired to cover maximum horizontal distance/range  = 45\u00b0  N.B:Rmax=u2g","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>13","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"MOTION : TYPES OF MOTION","question":"A body can undergo the following types of motion except","images":[],"options":{"A":"random","B":"translational","C":"rotational","D":"relative"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A body cannot undergo \"relative motion\". Relative motion usually involves two bodies.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>14","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"WORK, ENERGY AND POWER : CONCEPT OF ENERGY","question":"Which of the following graphs correctly represents the relationship between the kinetic energy (K.E) and the displacement (d) from point of release of a swinging pendulum bob?","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"","B":"","C":"","D":""},"answer":"B","explanation":"For a swinging pendulum, at the point of rest, i.e at equilibruim, the K.E is maximum, when displaced so that it moves through a certain height h, the K.E decreases to minimum and then back to maximum as it comes back to the equilibrium position    From the illustration above, we obtain the following graph.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>15","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"HOOKE\u2019S LAW, YOUNG\u2019S MODULES AND WORK DONE IN SPRINGS AND STRING :","question":"The energy stored in a spring of stiffness constant k = 2000Nm\u22121 when extended 4cm is","images":[],"options":{"A":"0.16J","B":"1.60J","C":"16.00J","D":"160.00J"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The spring constant = the measure of stiffness = 2000Nm\u22121    Energy stored in a spring = Work done to stretch it through a distance = change in potential energy     = kx2/12     = 2000\u00d7(0.04)2/2= 3.22=1.60J","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>16","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : LATENT HEAT","question":"Ice of mass 50g at 0\u00b0C was completely melted by 70% of the total heat energy supplied. Calculate the total heat energy supplied. (Specific latent heat of fusion of ice = 336Jg-1]","images":[],"options":{"A":"2400J","B":"6800J","C":"7251J","D":"24000J"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Mass of ice = 50g  Temperature of ice at 0\u00b0 to water at 0\u00b0C   I = 336 Fom, Q = ml  70% of Q = ml   70100\u00d7Q=ml  0.7Q = ml  0.7Q = 50 *times 336  Q=50\u00d73360.7=24000J","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>17","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"MACHINES :","question":"A plane is inclined at an angle \u03b8 to the horizontal. Its velocity ratio is","images":[],"options":{"A":"sin\u03b8","B":"tan\u03b8","C":"1sin\u03b8","D":"1tan\u03b8"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The velocity ratio of the inclined plane is:  V.R =1sin\u03b8","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>18","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : EFFECTS OF HEAT ON MATTER","question":"The diagram above illustrates a beaker of water being heated. It is observed that as the bubbles rise they get bigger in size. The reason for this observation is","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"water pressure on the bubbles decreases","B":"density of water increases with rise in temperature","C":"volume of water increases with rise in temperature","D":"atmospheric pressure on the bubbles decreases"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A decrease in the atmosphere pressure causes the bubble to get bigger","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>19","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : PRODUCTION OF ELECTRIC CURRENT","question":"Which of the following devices transforms light energy to electrical energy?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Bulb","B":"Television","C":"Solar cell","D":"Light emitting diode (LED)"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A solar cell is a device that transforms light energy into electrical energy. This is done through the photovoltaic effect, where photons from the light source are absorbed by the solar cell, causing electrons to be knocked loose from their atoms. These free electrons then move through the cell, creating an electric current.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>20","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"WORK, ENERGY AND POWER : CONCEPT OF ENERGY","question":"A motor of a corn mill machine operates on electrical energy of 1.44 \u00d7 105J. If one-quarter of the energy is wasted in the form of sound and heat, determine the efficiency of the machine.","images":[],"options":{"A":"25%","B":"36%","C":"64%","D":"75%"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Efficiency=Work outputWork input\u00d7100  Workoutput=34\u00d71.44\u00d7105(since14iswasted)  Work input = 1.44 \u00d7 105  Efficiency=34 \u00d7 1.44 \u00d7 1051.44 \u00d7 105\u00d71001  Efficiency=34\u00d7100=75%","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>21","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : LATENT HEAT","question":"Thermal energy added or removed from a substance that changes the state of the substance is called","images":[],"options":{"A":"latent heat","B":"heat of reaction","C":"calorimetry","D":"specific heat"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The thermal energy that is added or removed from a substance, causing it to change state, is called latent heat. This is the heat energy required to change the state of a substance without changing its temperature. For example, the heat energy required to change water from a solid (ice) to a liquid, or from a liquid to a gas (steam), is latent heat.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>22","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"FLUID AT REST : VOLUME, DENSITY AND RELATIVE DENSITY","question":"The maximum density of water occurs at a temperature of","images":[],"options":{"A":"0\u00b0C","B":"4\u00b0C","C":"37\u00b0C","D":"273\u00b0C"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The maximum density of water occurs at 4\u00b0C. This is an explanation to the anomalous expansion of water","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>23","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : VAPOUR AND VAPOUR PRESSURE","question":"A vapour whose molecules are in dynamic equilibrium with those of its own liquid is said to be","images":[],"options":{"A":"unsaturated","B":"gaseous","C":"saturated","D":"diffused"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Such vapour is said to be saturated. That is, the rate of evaporation is equal to the rate of condensation","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>24","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"PROPERTIES OF WAVES : SUPERPOSITION","question":"The diagram above illustrates two waves of equal amplitudes A and frequencies approaching each other.   When the two waves meet at a point 1 mid way between them, the vertical displacement of the resulting wave will be","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"0","B":"A/2","C":"A/4","D":"2A"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The waves will interfere constructively, so that a bigger wave will be formed   A + A = 2A","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>25","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : DISPERSION OF WHITE LIGHT","question":"A rainbow is formed when sunlight is incident on water droplets suspended in the air due to","images":[],"options":{"A":"diffraction","B":"refraction","C":"dispersion","D":"interference"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A rainbow is formed due to the dispersion of light. When sunlight passes through raindrops, it is refracted, or bent, and then reflected by the inside surface of the droplet. When the light exits the droplet, it is refracted again. The bending of light, or refraction, causes the different colors in the light spectrum to spread out and form a circle of colors. This is known as dispersion.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>26","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"SOUND WAVES : VIBRATION OF AIR IN PIPE \u2013 OPEN AND CLOSED PIPES","question":"Which of the following statements about the 3rd overtone of a vibrating air column of an open pipe is correct? It has","images":[],"options":{"A":"4 nodes","B":"5 nodes","C":"3 antinodes","D":"4 antinodes"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The diagram above represents an open pipe at the 3rd overtone. There are 5 antinodes and 4 nodes","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>27","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"PRODUCTION AND PROPAGATION OF WAVES : WAVEFORM","question":"Consider the wave equation:  y = 10sin7(x - 50t). What does the number 10 in the equation represent?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Acceleration","B":"Speed","C":"Amplitude","D":"Wavelength"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In the wave equation y = Asin(kx - wt), A represents the amplitude of the wave. The amplitude of a wave is the maximum displacement of the wave from its equilibrium position. In this case, the number 10 in the equation represents the amplitude of the wave.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>28","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"PROPERTIES OF WAVES : DIFFRACTION","question":"Plane waves passing through a narrow gap emerge as circular waves. This phenomenon is known as","images":[],"options":{"A":"interference","B":"dispersion","C":"refraction","D":"diffraction"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The phenomenom is diffraction. This occurs when waves propagating in group pass through a tiny orifice to form a circular wave.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>29","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"A ray of light incident at an angle \u03b8 in a rectangular prism grazes the surface of the prism on emerging from the prism. Determine the value of \u03b8. [Absolute refractive index of the material of the prism is 1.5].","images":[],"options":{"A":"41.8\u00b0","B":"48.2\u00b0","C":"60.8\u00b0","D":"90.0\u00b0"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Angle of incidence, i = \u03b8  Refractive index, n = 1.5  N.B: i = e (angle of emergence)  n=1sin\u03b8  1.5=1sin\u03b8  1.5sin\u03b8 = 1  sin\u03b8 = 0.66  \u03b8 = sin-10.66  \u03b8 = 41.8\u00b0","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>30","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"PRODUCTION AND PROPAGATION OF WAVES : SPEED, FREQUENCY AND WAVELENGTH","question":"The diagram above illustrates a wave set-up between two fixed ends 4.0m apart. If the speed of the wave is 1.0ms-1, its wavelength and frequency respectively are","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"1m, 0.25Hz","B":"2m, 0.25Hz","C":"2m, 0.50Hz","D":"4m, 0.50Hz"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Velocity, v = 1.0m/s    4m = \u03bb/2 + \u03bb/2 + \u03bb/2 + \u03bb/2  4m=4\u03bb2  8m = 4\u03bb  \u03bb=8m4=2m  V = f\u03bb ---------- (1)  1.0 = f \u00d7 2  f=12=0.5Hz  (\u03bb, f) = (2m, 0.5Hz)","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>31","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFLECTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES","question":"Two plane mirrors are inclined at an angle 20\u00b0 to each other. Determine the number of images formed when an object is placed between them.","images":[],"options":{"A":"17","B":"18","C":"19","D":"20"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Angle of inclination, \u03b8 = 20\u00b0, n = ?  Recall: For two mirrors inclined at \u03b8 to each other, the number of images formed will be   Fromn=360\u03b8-1  n=36020-1  n = 18 - 1 = 17 images","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>32","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : APPLICATION OF LENSES IN OPTICAL INSTRUMENTS","question":"A converging lens of focal length 10cm forms an erect image three times the size of a real object. Calculate the distance between the object and the image.","images":[],"options":{"A":"26.6cm","B":"11.1cm","C":"13.3cm","D":"20.0cm"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Focal length = 10cm  * The image is erect and magnified   Magnification, m = 3 = v/u  Image size (V) = 3U --------- (1)    N.B: When the converging lens forms a magnified, and erect image, the image is always virtual.  The distance between the object and the image is given as d.  d = v - u -------------- (2)  recall:1f=1v+1u  110=13u+1u  110=1+33u  3u = 40  u = 13.3cm  v = 3u = 39.9cm  d = v - u = 39.9cm - 13.3cm  d = 26.6cm","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>33","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"PRODUCTION AND PROPAGATION OF WAVES : FREQUENCY (F), WAVELENGTH(\ud835\udecc), PERIOD (T) AND VELOCITY (V)","question":"The inverse of the time required for a wave to complete one full cycle is called","images":[],"options":{"A":"wavelength","B":"period","C":"frequency","D":"amplitude"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The time taken for a wave to complete a cycle is known as period.  The inverse is called \"frequency\"","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>34","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"MAGNETIC FIELD : CONCEPT OF MAGNETIC FIELD","question":"Two bar magnets are placed near each other. Which of the following diagrams correctly illustrates the magnetic field pattern formed by the pair?","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"","B":"","C":"","D":""},"answer":"B","explanation":"The magnetic flux (lines of force) move from the N-pole to the S-pole.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>35","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CONCEPTS OF ELECTRIC FIELD, ELECTRIC FIELD INTENSITY (POTENTIAL GRADIENT) AND ELECTRIC POTENTIAL.","question":"The force per unit charge experienced at a point in a field is the","images":[],"options":{"A":"gravitational field strength","B":"electric potential","C":"electric field intensity","D":"magnetic field strength"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The force per unit charge experienced at a point in a field is the electric field intensity. It is a vector quantity and is defined as the force experienced by a unit positive charge placed at that point. Gravitational field strength is the force per unit mass experienced by a small test mass placed in the field. Electric potential is the work done per unit charge in bringing a positive point charge from infinity to a particular point in the field. Magnetic field strength is a measure of the intensity of the magnetic field at a particular location.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>36","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CONDUCTION THROUGH MATERIALS","question":"Which of the following objects is not a conductor of electricity?","images":[],"options":{"A":"The Earth","B":"Human body","C":"Iron rod","D":"Dry wood"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A conductor is a material that allows electric charge to move freely. Metals like iron rod are good conductors of electricity. The Earth and the human body are also conductors due to the presence of water and other substances that allow the flow of electric charge. However, dry wood is a poor conductor or insulator of electricity because it lacks free electrons that can move and carry electric charge.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>37","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CIRCUIT","question":"A circuit is set up as shown in the diagram above. When the key is closed, the reading on the ammeter will be","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"6A","B":"4A","C":"2A","D":"1A"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Resistor in parallel  RP=1x11+1=12  RS=1+12=32\u03a9  From ohm's law,  I=VR=33/2=3x23=63=2A","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>38","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"GRAVITATIONAL FIELD : GRAVITATIONAL POTENTIAL AND ESCAPE VELOCITY","question":"Which of the following statements is/are correct?  I. Gravitational potential due to a mass at a point a distance r away is proportional to r2  II. Gravitational field strength is a scalar quantity  III. Gravitational intensity is proportional to the weight of a unit mass","images":[],"options":{"A":"I, II and III","B":"III only","C":"II only","D":"I only"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Gravitationalpotential,V=-GMer  (1)iswrong,V\u03b11randnot\u03b11r2  All strengths/intensities are vector quantities. So (II) is wrong only (III) is correct.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>39","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"The diagrams below illustrate electrical connections to the element of an electric pressing iron. In which of the connections is the fuse correctly fixed?","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"","B":"","C":"","D":""},"answer":"B","explanation":"The fuse is correctly fixed in the diagram:","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>40","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"SIMPLE A.C. CIRCUITS : POWER","question":"A transformer connected to a 240Vrms has 3000 turns in its primary coil and 500 turns in its secondary coil. Calculate the output voltage","images":[],"options":{"A":"4000V","B":"400V","C":"40V","D":"4V"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Np = 3000turns   Ns = 500turns  Ep = 240Vrms  Es = ?  Es/Ep = Ns/Np  Es=Ep\u00d7NsNp  =240\u00d75003000=1203= 40V","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>41","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC ENERGY AND POWER","question":"A lamp rated 100W, 240V is lit for 5 hours. Calculate the cost of lighting the lamp if 1kWh of electrical energy cost \u20a65.","images":[],"options":{"A":"\u20a62.50","B":"\u20a63.20","C":"\u20a66.50","D":"\u20a69.60"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Power = 100w  Voltage = 240v  Time = 5 hrs  Energy consumed (w) = Pt= 100 *ties* 5 = 500whr  converting 10 kilowatt hour   500/1000 = 0.5Kwh  cost of lighting = 0.5\u00d7 5= \u20a62.5","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>42","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"A battery of emf 3.0V is connected across a potentiometer wire AB of 10\u03a9m-1 as illustrated in the diagram above. If the jocket J makes contact at the 30cm mark, determine the resistance of length AJ and voltage across AJ.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"3.0\u03a9 ; 0.9V","B":"3.0\u03a9 ; 3.0V","C":"3.3\u03a9 ; 0.3V","D":"3.3\u03a9 ; 9.0V"},"answer":"A","explanation":"E = 3V, R/l = 10\u03a9m-1  l = 30cm, R = ?  Rl=10  R0.3=10  R = 3\u03a9  EV=l1l2  V=3\u00d70.31  V = 0.9V","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>43","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTROMAGNETIC FIELD : POWER TRANSMISSION AND DISTRIBUTION","question":"The main reason why a.c is transmitted at very high voltage and low current is that it","images":[],"options":{"A":"flows faster through the conductor","B":"can be stepped down","C":"is cheaper to generate","D":"reduces heat loss"},"answer":"D","explanation":"This transmission mode reduces heat loss.  N.B = H = I2Rt  H \u03b1 I2  The higher the current, the higher the amount of heat generated.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>44","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CONCEPTS OF ELECTRIC FIELD, ELECTRIC FIELD INTENSITY (POTENTIAL GRADIENT) AND ELECTRIC POTENTIAL.","question":"The diagram above illustrate two charged bodies, X and Y separated by a distance r. Each body has charge q and mass m. Which of the following statements about the electrostatic force Fe and the gravitational force Fg acting between the bodies is correct?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"Fe is attraction while Fg is repulsion","B":"Both Fe and Fg are that of repulsion","C":"Both Fe and Fg are that of attraction","D":"Fe is repulsion while Fg is attraction"},"answer":"D","explanation":"There is always a gravitational force of ATTRACTION, but the electrostatic force of ATTRACTION OR REPULSION. For the charges, illustrated in the question, there will be a repulsion, since they are like charges","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>45","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"SIMPLE A.C. CIRCUITS : IMPEDANCE","question":"The opposition offered to an alternating current in a C - R series circuit is known as","images":[],"options":{"A":"impedance","B":"resistance","C":"reactance","D":"friction"},"answer":"A","explanation":"In an alternating current (AC) circuit containing both resistance (R) and capacitance (C), the total opposition to current flow is called impedance. Impedance takes into account both the resistance of the circuit and the reactance (opposition to current flow caused by capacitors and inductors). Therefore, the correct answer is option 1.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>46","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"WAVE-PARTICLE PARADOX : DUALITY OF MATTER","question":"Which of the following pairs of concepts constitutes complementary variables as expressed by the Heisenberg uncertainty principle?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Momentum and time","B":"Energy and acceleration","C":"Position and momentum","D":"Velocity and momentum"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The Heisenberg uncertainty principle states that the more precisely the position of a particle is determined, the less precisely its momentum can be known, and vice versa. Therefore, position and momentum are complementary variables.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>47","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE NUCLEUS : COMPOSITION OF THE NUCLEUS","question":"The nucleon number of an atom is the total number of","images":[],"options":{"A":"electrons and protons","B":"electrons and neutrons","C":"neutrons minus electrons","D":"protons and neutrons"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The nucleon number/mass number of an atom is the number of protons and neutrons in the nucleus of the atom.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>48","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE ATOM : ENERGY QUANTIZATION","question":"n = \u03b1 ----------------- 0.0eV  E = 3 ----------------- - 1.6eV  E = 2 ----------------- -3.7eV  E = 1 ----------------- -5.5eV  E = 0 ----------------- -10.4 eV  The energy levels in the mercury atom is illustrated in the diagram above. Calculate the ionisation energy of the atom.","images":[],"options":{"A":"+21.2eV","B":"+10.4eV","C":"-10.4eV","D":"-21.2eV"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The ionisation energy of an atom is the energy required to remove an electron from the ground state (lowest energy level) of the atom to infinity. In the given diagram, the ground state energy level is -10.4 eV. Therefore, the ionisation energy is the absolute value of this energy level, which is +10.4 eV.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>49","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE NUCLEUS : RADIOACTIVITY","question":"Which of the following statements about gamma radiation is correct? Gamma radiation can","images":[],"options":{"A":"be seen by the naked eye","B":"not pass through an aluminium foil","C":"be present naturally in our surroundings","D":"be used as a tracer"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Gamma radiation can be used as a tracer in medical imaging and industrial processes to track the movement of substances.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2017>50","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTROMAGNETIC WAVES: : ELECTROMAGNETIC SPECTRUM","question":"Radio waveMicro waveInfrared wavePQRGamma ray  The table above shows the components of electromagnetic spectrum in order of increasing frequency. Which of the following sets correctly identifies P, Q and R respectively?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Visible, ultraviolet, X-ray","B":"X-ray, visible, ultraviolet","C":"Ultraviolet, visible, X-ray","D":"X-ray, ultraviolet, visible"},"answer":"A","explanation":"In order of increasing frequencies, the electromagnetic spectrum is arranged as thus  Radiowave  &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp \u2193  Microwave  &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp \u2193  Infrared wave  &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp \u2193  Visible light  &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp \u2193  Ultraviolet rays  &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp \u2193  X-rays  &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp \u2193  Gamma rays","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"}];